    id: 108, ring: "local", category: "governance",
    headline: "My Daughter Had a Screaming Meltdown Over an iPad. It Was the Moment I Realized This Isn't Her Fault.",
    preview: "I am a parent at a public school in Oakville. Last month my eight year old had an outburst over screen time unlike anything I had seen from her before. It made me look at my own habits first.",
    signature: "A Parent · Oakville", region: "Oakville, Ontario", timeAgo: "9 hours ago", readTime: "5 min read", upvotes: 6204,
    gradient: "linear-gradient(135deg, #6B3A1A 0%, #2D1508 100%)",
    imageUrl: "data:image/jpeg;base64,",
    body: [
      "I am a parent at a public school here in Oakville. Last month my eight year old had a screaming, kicking meltdown when I took away her iPad that lasted almost twenty minutes. It was not a tantrum like the ones I remember from when she was three. It was something closer to withdrawal. I did not have a better word for it at the time and I am not sure I have a better one now.",
      "I talked to other parents at pickup the next day, carefully, the way you do when you are not sure if you are the only one. I was not the only one.",
      "Three other families described almost the exact same thing within the last few months. Outbursts that did not match the trigger. Kids who could regulate themselves reasonably well a year ago and now cannot get through an iPad being taken away without falling apart.",
      "I want to be honest about something before I go further. My first instinct was to blame the school, the apps, the device makers, anyone but myself. But the truth is I am the one who handed her that iPad in the first place, on a long car ride, because it was easier than dealing with her boredom in the moment. I have done that a hundred times since because it works in the short term and I am tired.",
      "I do not think the answer is banning technology. I think the answer is much less comfortable than that. It is parents like me looking honestly at how often we reach for a screen to manage a feeling instead of sitting with our kid through it. The social world around technology will not change because a school sends home a pamphlet. It changes because parents change first, and that is a hard thing to ask of people who are already stretched thin.",
      "I am not writing this to blame other parents. I am writing it because I needed to say it somewhere honest, and admitting it to the other parents at pickup is harder than admitting it here.",
    ],
    spawnedQuestion: null,
