    id: 109, ring: "global", category: "economy",
    headline: "I Have Worked for Three People Who Inherited Everything. None of Them Have Ever Been Afraid.",
    preview: "I have spent eleven years as a personal assistant to wealthy families. I have seen how differently the world treats people who have never once worried about money, and how little most of them notice it.",
    signature: "K. Whitfield", region: "Manchester, United Kingdom", timeAgo: "3 hours ago", readTime: "6 min read", upvotes: 9841,
    gradient: "linear-gradient(135deg, #1A3A6B 0%, #0A1A35 100%)",
    imageUrl: "data:image/jpeg;base64,",
    body: [
      "I have spent eleven years working as a personal assistant to wealthy families. Three different employers, three different fortunes, all of them inherited rather than built. I want to be careful here because this is not an attack on any one person. It is an observation about something I have watched up close for over a decade that I think matters more than people realize.",
      "None of the people I have worked for have ever been afraid of their bank account. Not once. Not during a divorce, not during a recession, not during a pandemic that put people I grew up with out of work for over a year. The fear that organizes most people's relationship with money simply does not exist for them, and because it has never existed, most of them do not know it is missing.",
      "I do not say this with bitterness. Some of the people I have worked for are kind, generous, thoughtful employers. But I have watched them make decisions — about employees, about charity, about policy positions they casually mention at dinner — with a confidence that comes from never having needed to get something right because their life depended on it.",
      "There is a kind of understanding that only comes from scarcity. Knowing exactly how many days until payday. Doing the math on whether the car will make it another month. Choosing between two things you need because you cannot afford both. I do not believe that understanding can be taught, read about, or absorbed through proximity. I believe it has to be lived.",
      "This is why I find myself skeptical, not of wealthy people as individuals, but of inherited wealth as a qualification for understanding the lives of people who do not have it. Empathy is real and many wealthy people have plenty of it. But empathy is not the same thing as comprehension, and I have spent eleven years watching the difference between the two up close.",
    ],
